\begin_layout Standard
In response to such objections, however, others argue that the harms caused
 by overconsumption from behavioral biases are themselves regressive, so
 a corrective tax might confer greater benefits on the poor than the rich.
 For example, smoking and sugary drink consumption cause lung cancer, diabetes,
 and other health problems that disproportionately affect the poor.
