\begin_layout Subsection
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with a conventional static optimal taxation setting: consumers
 have multidimensional heterogeneous types 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\varTheta\subset\mathbb{R}_{+}^{n}$
\end_inset

, distributed with measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 They supply labor to generate pre-tax income 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, which is subject to a nonlinear tax 
\begin_inset Formula $T(z)$
\end_inset

.
 Net income is spent on a two goods: a numeraire consumption good 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sin good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, with pre-tax price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, which is subject to a linear commodity tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the consumer's budget constraint is 
\begin_inset Formula $c+(p+t)s\le z-T(z).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each consumer chooses a bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,s,z)$
\end_inset

, subject to her budget constraint, to maximize 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

decision utility
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U(c,s,z;\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be increasing and weakly concave in its first two arguments,
 and decreasing and strictly concave in the third.
 Decision utility may differ from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normative utility
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $V(c,s,z;\theta)$
\end_inset

, which the consumers would choose to maximize if they were fully informed
 and free from behavioral biases.
 Sin good consumption also generates a fiscal cost to the government of
 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 per unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 consumed.
 Pecuniary fiscal externalities are a natural case for sin goods such as
 sugar-sweetened beverages and cigarettes that raise the health care costs
 for public programs like Medicare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The policymaker selects taxes 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to maximize normative utility, aggregated across all consumers using type-speci
fic Pareto weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\theta)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{T,t}\left[\int_{\Theta}\alpha(\theta)[V(c(\theta),s(\theta),z(\theta);\theta)]d\mu(\theta)\right],\label{eq:objective}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

subject to a government budget constraint, which includes the externality
 costs of sin good consumption,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\Theta}(ts(\theta)+T(z(\theta)-es(\theta))d\mu(\theta)\ge R\label{eq:budget constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and to consumer optimization
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ c(\theta),s(\theta),z(\theta)\right\} =\arg\max_{\left\{ c,s,z\right\} }U(c,s,z;\theta)\mathrm{\quad{s.t.}\quad}c+(p+t)s\leq z-T(z)\;\text{for all}\;\theta.\label{eq:ic constraints}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 can capture a variety of different psychological biases.
 For example, consumers may have incorrect beliefs about certain attributes
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, such as calorie content, future health costs, or energy efficiency 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "attari2010,Bollinger2011,allcott2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, consumers may have limited attention or salience bias with
 respect to certain attributes of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Allcott2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, present focus may lead consumers to underweight the future health
 costs of some goods (e.g, potato chips or cigarettes) as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gruber2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ODonoghue2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Our framework allows us to treat present focus as a bias.
 However, our framework also allows us to study other welfare criteria that
 may be applied to the model—for example, the policy might place some normative
 weight both on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

future-oriented self
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in-the-moment self.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key goal of our theoretical analysis is to derive optimal tax formulas
 that can accommodate a variety of possible consumer biases while still
 being empirically implementable.
 We do this by constructing a price metric for consumer bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s(p+t,y,z,\theta)$
\end_inset

 be the sin good consumption chosen at total price 
\begin_inset Formula $p+t$
\end_inset

 by a type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 consumer who earns 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and has disposable income 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that because our model allows utility to not be weakly separable
 in leisure and consumption of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 depends not only on disposable income but also on earned income 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Analogously, define 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{V}(p+t,y,z,\theta)$
\end_inset

 to be the amount of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 that would be chosen if the consumer were maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 instead.
 We define the bias, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(p+t,y,z,\theta)$
\end_inset

, as the value for which 
\begin_inset Formula $s(p+t,y,z,\theta)=s^{V}(p+t-\gamma,y-s\gamma,z,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 In words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is equal to the compensated price reduction that produces the same change
 in demand as the bias does.
 In terms of primitives, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{U'_{s}}{U'_{c}}-\frac{V'_{s}}{V'_{c}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The first-order condition for consumer choice is 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{s}(c,s,z)/U'_{c}(c,s,z)=p+t$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $s\cdot(p+t)+c=z-T(z)$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{s}(c,s,z)/V'_{c}(c,s,z)=p+t-\gamma$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s\cdot(p+t-\gamma)+c=z-T(z)-s\gamma$
\end_inset

, from which the statement follows.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Throughout, we will use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{x}$
\end_inset

 to denote the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f''_{xy}$
\end_inset

 for the the cross-partial derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, etc.
 When no ambiguity arises, we sometimes suppress some arguments and write,
 for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\theta)$
\end_inset

 for concision.) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\theta)>0,$
\end_inset

 this means that type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 consumers over-consume 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 relative to their normative preferences, whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\theta)<0$
\end_inset

 means that type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 consumers under-consume.
 Throughout the paper, we will assume that the sole source of disagreement
 between the consumer and policy maker is about the merits of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

; we do not focus on labor supply misoptimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The statistic can be quantified by comparing consumers' choices in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

biased
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

debiased
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 states, as we do in our empirical application.
 Other examples that informally employ this definition of bias include 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Chetty2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "taubinsky2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, who quantify the (average) value of tax salience as the change in up-front
 prices that would alter demand as much as a debiasing intervention that
 displays tax-inclusive prices.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Allcott2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 by measuring consumers' demand responses to an experimental intervention
 that targets informational and attentional biases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To represent the policymaker's inequality aversion concisely, we employ
 the notion, common in the optimal taxation literature, of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

social marginal welfare weights
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

—the social value (from the policymaker's perspective) of a marginal unit
 of consumption for a particular consumer, measured in terms of public funds.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(\theta):=\alpha(\theta)V'_{c}/\lambda,\label{eq:smwwdef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{c}$
\end_inset

 represents the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with respect to its first argument, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the marginal value of public funds (i.e., the multiplier on the government
 budget constraint at the optimum).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This definition implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 represents the social value of a unit of marginal composite consumption
 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, rather than sin good consumption.
 When agents make rational decisions about consumption of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, this distinction is immaterial due to the envelope theorem.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 These weights are endogenous to the tax system, but are useful for characterizi
ng the necessary conditions that must hold at the optimum.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{g}=\int_{\varTheta}g(\theta)d\mu(\theta)$
\end_inset

 to denote the average marginal social welfare weight.
 If there are no income effects on consumption and labor supply, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{g}=1$
\end_inset

 by construction.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because the Pareto weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\theta)$
\end_inset

 are exogenous, and because 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 produce identical behavior (and identical choice-based measures of bias)
 up to monotonic transformations, the social marginal welfare weights reflect
 a policymaker's or society's normative preference for reducing wealth inequalit
y—they cannot be inferred by observing behavior.
 As in the rest of the optimal taxation literature, our formulas for optimal
 taxes will thus depend both on observable behavior (and people's quantifiable
 mistakes) and on the policymaker's (or society's) inequality aversion,
 as encoded by these weights.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Our Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We derive an expression for the optimal sin tax using variational calculus
 arguments.
 This generates a first-order (necessary) condition for the optimal sin
 tax in terms of empirically estimable sufficient statistics and social
 marginal welfare weights.
 These statistics are themselves endogenous to the tax system, and so this
 expression should not be understood as a closed-form expression for the
 optimal tax.
 However, to the extent that these statistics are stable around modest variation
s in tax policy, we can approximate the optimal tax by evaluating the statistics
 at the current tax policy.
 In Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:simulations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we calibrate two different structural models that account for the endogeneity,
 and we show that the resulting optimal taxes are very close to those computed
 using estimates of the sufficient statistics at the current tax system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before formally defining the elasticity concepts and presenting the optimal
 tax formula, we briefly summarize the core economic forces that correspond
 to our elasticity concepts and that feature in the formula.
 Intuitively, any variation in the sin tax has three main effects.
 First, a higher sin tax has a direct (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mechanical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) effect on government revenue and on consumers' post-tax incomes.
 The social welfare consequences of this effect depend on the marginal value
 of public funds, and on whether the increased tax burden is shouldered
 more by those with higher or lower marginal utility of money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, an increase in the sin tax leads to substitution away from the sin
 good, which reduces the revenue collected from taxing the sin good.
 In the absence of externalities or internalities, the envelope theorem
 implies the loss in sin tax revenues is the only consequential effect.
 In the presence of externalities and/or internalities, the behavior change
 is beneficial because it reduces externalities from consumption, and because
 consumers now consume less of a good that they have been overconsuming.
 The internality correction benefits are highest when the consumers with
 the highest biases are also most elastic to the sin tax.
 Moreover, when the low-income consumers are the most responsive and/or
 the most biased, the internality benefits of behavior change have the additiona
l virtue of being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

progressive.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, the sin tax could affect consumers' labor supply decisions.
 Imagine that the sin good is a normal good, so that if a consumer chooses
 to earn more, she consumes more of the sin good.
 In this case, increasing the sin tax indirectly increases the marginal
 tax burden from choosing higher earnings.
 This disincentive for higher labor supply would then lead to lower income
 tax revenue.
 The converse holds for inferior goods.
 Consequently, when the consumption of a sin good is decreasing with income,
 it is crucial to determine whether this is because it is an inferior good,
 or because preferences for this good are negatively correlated with earnings
 ability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This potential earnings response may substantially affect the optimal sin
 tax even if consumers spend only a small share of their budget on the sin
 good.
 Intuitively, what matters is the change in earnings due to the sin tax
 
\emph on
as a share of expenditures on the sin good
\emph default
—and that share may be substantial even if spending on the sin good is small.
 This channel of behavioral response is the foundation for the classic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Atkinson1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 result.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is also possible that taxes on items that constitute a small share of
 consumers' budgets might not be salient when labor supply decisions are
 made.
 Nonsalience is an alternative form of behavioral misoptimization which
 may lead to departures from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Atkinson1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and though it is beyond the scope of this paper, we consider it in our
 companion paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "ALT2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are also higher order effects that are present in the general formula
 in the appendix that are negligible under the simplifying assumptions we
 make in our main theoretical result.
 These include considerations such as the fact that changes in labor supply
 can also affect consumption of the sin good through the income effects
 channel, and that at a given income level there may be a covariance between
 income effects and internalities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Elasticity Concepts, Sufficient Statistics, and Simplifying Assumptions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:set-up"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal sin tax depends on three types of sufficient statistics: elasticitie
s, money-metric measure of bias, and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

progressivity of bias correction.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 We describe these statistics here, and collect them in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:notation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for reference.
 These statistics are understood to be endogenous to the tax regime 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,T)$
\end_inset

, though we suppress those arguments for notational simplicity.
 We begin by defining the elasticities related to sin good consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(\theta)$
\end_inset

: the price elasticity of demand for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 from type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, formally equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(\frac{ds(\theta)}{dt}\right)\frac{p+t}{s(\theta)}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that the price elasticity of demand equals the tax elasticity
 of demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{c}(\theta)$
\end_inset

: the compensated price elasticity of demand for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(\left.\frac{ds(\theta)}{dt}\right|_{u}\right)\frac{p+t}{s(\theta)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\theta)$
\end_inset

: the income effect on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 expenditure, equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta-\zeta^{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(\theta)$
\end_inset

: the causal income elasticity of demand for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dz}s\left(p+t,z-T(z),z;\theta\right)\cdot\frac{z}{s}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A change in net earnings may come from either a change in labor supply or
 a change in non-labor income (e.g., due to a tax level reduction).
 If sin good consumption and labor are weakly separable in the utility function,
 sin good consumption will respond identically to either type of change
 in earnings.
 In that case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(\theta)$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\eta(\theta)}{p+t}\cdot\frac{z(\theta)}{s(\theta)}(1-T'(z(\theta)))$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 quantifies the sin good response to an increase in earnings 
\emph on
from labor
\emph default
, for example due to a local reduction in marginal income tax rates.
 Weak separability implies that the change of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 with response to income shock 
\begin_inset Formula $dz$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ds}{dz}$
\end_inset

