\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assump:unidimensional"

\end_inset

(b) and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assump:additional"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 go to zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the purpose of building intuition, note that Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:t opt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be rearranged as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=\underbrace{\bar{\gamma}(1+\sigma)+e}_{\text{corrective motive}}+\frac{1}{\frac{d\bar{s}}{dt}}\underbrace{Cov\left[g(z),s_{pref}(z)\right]}_{\text{redistributive motive}}.\label{eq:t opt 1 alt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:t opt 1 alt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that the optimal tax is the combination of two main terms.
 The first term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}(1+\sigma)+e$
\end_inset

, corresponds to the corrective motive of the tax, and rises with both the
 negative externality 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and internality (average marginal bias) 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 The latter is scaled by 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\sigma$
\end_inset

, illustrating a key difference between externalities and internalities:
 the magnitude of correction for internalities—but not externalities—depends
 on whether the bias is bigger for the rich or the poor, and on whether
 the rich or the poor have more elastic demand.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This asymmetry is not an artifact of the assumption that externalities fall
 on the government's budget.
 We could alternatively allow for more flexible externalities which are
 nonlinear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}$
\end_inset

 and heterogeneous across agents, reducing each consumer's net income by
 a type-specific amount 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\bar{s})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the consumer's budget constraint in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ic constraints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 would instead be written 
\begin_inset Formula $c+(p+t)s\leq z-T(z)-E(\bar{s})$
\end_inset

.
 We can then define 
\begin_inset Formula $e=E'_{\bar{s}}(\bar{s})$
\end_inset

, and the optimal tax formulas in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "prop:general opt tax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 remain the same.
 That is, under heterogeneous externalities one should set the externality
 correction equal to the average marginal externality; however, there is
 no covariance with individual demand elasticity or the level of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 consumption, as is the case with internalities.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fn:heterogeneous externalities"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, the internality costs from an consumer's overconsumption fall
 back on that consumer, so they are scaled by the consumer's social marginal
 welfare weight.
 In contrast, the externality generated by any given consumer's consumption
 is borne by the whole population, and thus receives the same weight regardless
 of whose consumption generates it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second term, proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov\left[g(z),s_{pref}(z)\right]$
\end_inset

, corresponds to the redistributive motive of the tax.
 This term depends on the extent to which sin good consumption acts as a
 tag for ability.
 As a result, it depends on the covariation of welfare weights with only
 that component of consumption which is driven by preference heterogeneity.
 Intuitively, this term represents the power of the sin tax to accomplish
 redistribution which cannot already be achieved via income taxation.
 The importance of this term relative to the corrective component depends
 on how responsive consumption of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}$
\end_inset

 is to the tax: the more consumer behavior responds to the tax, the less
 important the redistributive motive relative to the corrective motive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The income tax formula is a slight modification of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jacquet2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, with the addition of the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[(g(z^{*})\gamma(\theta)+e-t)\frac{\xi(\theta)s(\theta)\zeta_{z}^{c}(\theta)}{\zeta_{z}^{c}(z^{*})z^{*}}|z(\theta)=z^{*}\right]$
\end_inset

, which accounts for the way a perturbation of the marginal income tax rate
 affects consumption of the sin good through the channel of changing consumers'
 earnings.
\end_layout

