LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:t opt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has a number of special cases which illustrate important insights about
 the forces governing the optimal tax.
 We highlight three special cases of particular interest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Special Case 1: No inequality aversion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If social marginal welfare weights are constant (implying the policymaker
 has no desire to redistribute marginal resources from high to low income
 consumers), then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=\bar{\gamma}+e.\label{eq:no inequality aversion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This matches the core principal of Pigouvian taxation and the typical sin
 tax results in the behavioral economics literature (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt*
key "ODonoghue2006,Mullainathan2012,Allcott2014,Allcott2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 This special case obtains either if welfare weights are constant across
 incomes (e.g., if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

) or if there is no income inequality (so that all consumers have the same
 marginal utility of consumption).
 In both cases, the optimal commodity tax must exactly offset the average
 marginal bias plus the externality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Special Case 2: No (correlated) preference heterogeneity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When differences in consumption are due purely to differences in income,
 regressive consequences of a sin tax can be perfectly offset by modifications
 to the income tax.
 Equivalently, all feasible distribution can be carried out most efficiently
 through the income tax itself, and the redistributive motive in Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:t opt 1 alt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is zero.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $s'_{pref}(z)=0$
\end_inset

 need not imply that preferences for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are homogeneous; only that they are not correlated with earnings ability.
 This special case corresponds to Assumption 3 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Saez2002a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who shows that the Atkinson-Stiglitz result continues to hold under this
 assumption.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Therefore in this case the optimal sin tax is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=\bar{\gamma}\left(1+\sigma\right)+e.\label{cor: income effects-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In contrast to Special Case 1, inequality aversion still plays a role in
 the size of the optimal commodity tax, as reflected by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 term.
 For a given average marginal bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, a relative increase in the biases or elasticities of low-income consumers
 increases 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and thus increases the social welfare benefit of bias correction.
 When bias and elasticity are constant across incomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>0$
\end_inset

, and the size of the optimal tax will exceed the optimal Pigouvian tax
 that prevails absent any inequality aversion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Special Case 3: No corrective concerns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A third important special case is when both internalities and externalities
 are equal to zero, so that only distributional concerns are relevant.
 In this case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{t}{p+t}=-\frac{Cov\left[g(z),s_{pref}(z)\right]}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}.\label{eq: A-S generalization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: A-S generalization"

\end_inset

 bears a striking resemblance to Diamond's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Diamond1975"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

many-person Ramsey tax rule.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Diamond1975"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 studies a Ramsey framework in which the income tax is constrained to be
 a lump-sum transfer, and he obtains almost the same expression as Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: A-S generalization"

\end_inset

, except with 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{pref}(z)$
\end_inset

 replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{s}(z)$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: A-S generalization"

\end_inset

 generalizes that result, showing that in the presence of a nonlinear income
 tax, the optimal commodity tax still resembles the familiar inverse elasticity
 rule, with the modification that instead of taxing goods that high-earners
 
\emph on
consume
\emph default
, the planner taxes goods that they 
\emph on
prefer.

\emph default
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: A-S generalization"

\end_inset

 also generalizes the Atkinson-Stiglitz theorem to the case of arbitrary
 preference heterogeneity.
 The Atkinson-Stiglitz theorem itself obtains as a special case of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: A-S generalization"

\end_inset

 when all variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 consumption is driven by income effects, which then implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{pref}\equiv0$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Further insights and intuition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the three special cases above, there are a few other insights
 from Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:general opt tax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that relate to results elsewhere in the literature.
 First, Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:t opt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 holds when 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}=0$
\end_inset

, which may arise even with non-zero internalities if the consumers who
 over-consume (or under-consume) the good are inelastic to the tax (or subsidy).
 A striking implication of the result then is that when lower-income consumers
 prefer the good more, the optimal sin tax will be negative (a sin subsidy).
 This captures the spirit of a key result of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bernheim2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 about the optimality of subsidizing addictive goods when the marginal utility
 of income is increasing with the consumption of the addictive good.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bernheim2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 over-consumption of the good is a consequence of cue-triggered neural processes
 that render the consumer inelastic to prices, the average bias of consumers
 who are elastic to the tax is zero.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Although the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bernheim2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 result that the sin good should be subsidized is seemingly in stark contrast
 to the sin tax results of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ODonoghue2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and elsewhere, our general tax formula clarifies the economic forces that
 lead to each result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second key insight from Proposition 1 involves the role of the demand
 elasticity in governing the relative importance of corrective and redistributiv
e concerns.
 As is evident from Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:t opt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, when the demand elasticity grows large, the redistributive motive becomes
 small and the optimal tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}(\bar{g}+\sigma)+e$
\end_inset

, corresponding to Special Case 2 above.
 At the opposite extreme, when the elasticity grows small, the corrective
 motive becomes negligible and the optimal tax approaches the expression
 in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: A-S generalization"

\end_inset

 above.
 More generally, if preference heterogeneity accounts for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 share of the decrease in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 consumption across incomes, then for a sufficiently low elasticity, the
 optimal tax becomes negative (a subsidy).
 Intuitively, if consumers do not respond to commodity taxes, then such
 taxes become a powerful instrument to enact redistribution through targeted
 subsidies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together, these results show how the price elasticity of demand modulates
 the role of consumer bias in determining both the sign and magnitude of
 the optimal commodity tax.
 Perhaps most importantly, the demand elasticity also provides practical
 guidance on how 
\emph on
sensitive 
\emph default
the optimal tax is to different values of the bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 and the externality 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
 A lower elasticity dampens the responsiveness of the optimal tax to the
 bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, since the corrective benefits in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:t opt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 depend on the products 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}^{c}\bar{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}^{c}e$
\end_inset

.
 Simply put, learning that the average marginal bias or the externality
 are $1 per unit higher than previously thought does not imply that the
 optimal tax should increase by 
\begin_inset Formula $\$1$
\end_inset

—the optimal adjustment could be higher or lower, depending on the demand
 elasticity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:general opt tax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 clarifies the role of revenue recycling—the possibility of using sin tax
 revenues to offset their regressivity.
 By including a nonlinear income tax, this model allows for tax revenues
 to be redistributed in a means-tested fashion.
 Yet our results also explain why such recycling may not be 
\emph on
optimal
\emph default
.
 If sin good consumption differences are driven by income effects, then
 the sin tax and income tax cause similar labor supply distortions.
 In this case, when a corrective sin tax is implemented, the optimal income
 tax should be jointly reformed to be more progressive, effectively recycling
 sin tax revenues in a progressive manner.
 (This corresponds to Special Case 2 above, and accords with the argument
 behind the quote from Jim Kenney in the introduction.) However, if sin good
 consumption differences are driven by preference heterogeneity, then sin
 good consumption serves as a tag that is useful for redistribution, even
 in the presence of the optimal income tax.
 In this case the optimal sin tax is reduced, in order to effectively subsidize
 the sin good for redistributive reasons relative to the pure Pigovian benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimal Sin Tax at a Fixed Income Tax
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:fixed T"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tax authorities may not be able to optimize the income tax system at the
 same time that a sin tax is imposed and, indeed, the income tax may be
 suboptimal from their perspective.
 For example, in the U.S., many SSB taxes are set by cities that do not control
 the income tax structure.
 In such cases, the optimal sin tax satisfies the following condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:FixedIncomeTax"

\end_inset

If Assumptions 1 through 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assump:additional"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 hold, then the optimal commodity tax is approximated by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\approx\frac{\bar{\gamma}(1+\sigma)+e-\frac{p}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}\left(Cov\left[g(z),s(z)\right]+\mathcal{A}\right)}{1+\frac{1}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}\left(Cov\left[g(z),s(z)\right]+\mathcal{A}\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{T'(z(\theta))}{1-T'(z(\theta))}\zeta_{z}(\theta)s(\theta)\xi(\theta)\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression for the constrained optimal SSB tax resembles that in Proposition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:t opt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, but it replaces the term 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov\left[g(z),s_{pref}(z)\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov\left[g(z),s(z)\right]+\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 This reflects the fact that under the optimal income tax, the fiscal externalit
y from income adjustments in response to the tax (captured by the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:FixedIncomeTax"

\end_inset

) is exactly equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov\left[g(z),s_{inc}(z)\right]$
\end_inset

, leaving 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov\left[g(z),s_{pref}(z)\right]$
\end_inset

 as the residual term.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the income elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

.Intuitively, when the sin good is a normal good, a higher sin tax is equivalent
 to an increase in the marginal income tax rate.
 The converse obtains when the sin good is an inferior good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Multiple Sin Goods and Substitution
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:multiple"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus far, our model has involved only a single sin good.
 We extend our results in a number of ways to account for substitution between
 sin goods.
 In Online Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:Many-Dimensions prop"

\end_inset

 we derive a general formula for the optimal 
\emph on
set
\emph default
 of sin taxes, allowing for a general relationship between cross-price elasticit
ies and biases.
 In Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:composite prop"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we also characterize results when the sin good 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a composite good consisting of several different items, such as soft
 drinks of various sizes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A third important and practical case is when the policymaker is constrained
 to tax only one of the sin goods.
 For example, the policymaker may impose a sin tax on sugary drinks, while
 not taxing other sugary foods like ice cream and candy bars.
 We focus on this case here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 denote consumption of the taxed sin good sold at price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\dots,r_{N}$
\end_inset

 denote consumption of other sin goods sold at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},\dots p_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}=ps$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=p_{n}r_{n}$
\end_inset

 denote the pre-tax expenditures of the respective goods.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\theta):=-\frac{\sum_{n}\frac{dx_{n}(\theta)}{dt}}{\frac{dx_{s}(\theta)}{dt}}$
\end_inset

 to measure how much of the reduction in pre-tax expenditures on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is reallocated to expenditures on the other sin goods 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 in response to a local increase in the sin tax.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We continue to let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 denote the money-metric measures of the bias and externality on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, respectively, and we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{n}$
\end_inset

 analogously for the other sin goods 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 These measures are hard to compare, however, because each is in units of
 dollars per unit of the respective sin good (e.g., dollars per ounce, dollars
 per pack, etc).
 We therefore convert these to unitless measures by dividing by the pre-tax
 price of the respective sin good: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{s}:=\gamma/p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{e}_{s}:=e/p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{n}:=\gamma_{n}/p_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{e}_{n}:=e_{n}/p_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We then define 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{r}(\theta):=\frac{\sum_{n}\tilde{\gamma}_{n}(\theta)\frac{dx_{n}(\theta)}{dt}}{\sum_{n}\frac{dx_{n}(\theta)}{dt}}$
\end_inset

 as the expenditure elasticity-weighted average bias of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, and we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}(\theta):=\tilde{\gamma}_{s}(\theta)-\varphi(\theta)\tilde{\gamma}_{r}(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 In words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}(\theta)$
\end_inset

 measures the extent to which consumers over-estimate the value of the marginal
 change in consumption of all sin goods that is induced by an increase in
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Using this definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}(\theta)$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tilde{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tilde{\gamma}}(z)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 in exact analogue to the single sin good case.
 Finally, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{e}_{r}:=\frac{\sum_{n}\tilde{e}_{n}\frac{d\bar{x}_{n}}{dt}}{\sum_{n}\frac{d\bar{x}_{n}}{dt}}$
\end_inset

 as the expenditure-elasticity-weighted externality for untaxed sin goods
 for the whole population, and we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tilde{e}}:=\tilde{e}_{s}-\frac{\sum_{n}\frac{d\bar{x}_{n}}{dt}}{\frac{d\bar{x}_{s}}{dt}}\tilde{e}_{r}$
\end_inset

 to denote the expenditure-weighted externality, per unit change in pre-tax
 expenditures on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Using these definitions, the formula for the optimal commodity tax is analogous
 to that in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:general opt tax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:substitution to other sins"

\end_inset

If Assumptions 1 through 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assump:additional"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 hold and all sin goods are a small share of the consumers' total expenditures,
 then the optimal commodity tax at any fixed tax is approximated by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\approx p\frac{\bar{\tilde{\gamma}}(1+\tilde{\sigma})+\bar{\tilde{e}}-\frac{1}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}\left(Cov\left[g(z),s(z)\right]+\mathcal{A}\right)}{1+\frac{1}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}Cov\left[g(z),s(z)\right]+\mathcal{A}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{T'(z(\theta))}{1-T'(z(\theta))}\zeta_{z}(\theta)s(\theta)\xi(\theta)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 If the income tax is optimal, then the optimal commodity tax is approximated
 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\approx p\frac{\bar{\tilde{\gamma}}(1+\tilde{\sigma})+\bar{\tilde{e}}-\frac{1}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}Cov\left[g(z),s_{pref}(z)\right]}{1+\frac{1}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}Cov\left[g(z),s_{pref}(z)\right]}.\label{eq:t opt substitution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We provide a proof of this result, as well as a formula for the optimal
 income tax, in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app: substitution to other sins"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The key difference between this formula and the formulas with a single
 sin good is in the construction of the bias and externality variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}(\theta)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{e}$
\end_inset

.
 In the absence of cross-price effects, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\bar{\tilde{\gamma}}=p\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\bar{\tilde{e}}=e$
\end_inset

, and thus the formula reduces to our initial result.
 In general, substitution to untaxed sin goods will reduce the total average
 marginal bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tilde{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 and the average marginal externality 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tilde{e}}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if the normalized values of bias and externality are all equal
 across the sin goods, and if the cross-price expenditure outflow 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is equal to 30%, then we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\tilde{\gamma}=0.7\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\bar{\tilde{e}}=0.7e$
\end_inset

; that is, the corrective benefits are reduced by 30 percent.
 On the other hand, if untaxed sin goods are complements—for example, if
 drinking lowers inhibitions to smoking or using drugs—then the optimal
 sin tax is higher.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula can also be applied to study 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

leakage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: cases in which consumers shop outside the jurisdiction to avoid a local
 sin tax.
 In this case, we can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 as the sin good available across the border, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{r}=\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is simply the change in demand for the sin good across the border divided
 by the change in demand for the sin good within the taxed jurisdiction.
 Because leakage is typically relevant at the city level but not the national
 level, optimal tax rates will typically be lower for city-level taxes than
 for nationwide taxes.
\end_layout

