\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we estimate the price and income elasticities of demand,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

, and how they vary by income.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{it}$
\end_inset

 denote Homescan SSB purchases (in liters per adult equivalent) by household
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{it}$
\end_inset

 denote the price per liter of household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's SSBs in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}_{it}$
\end_inset

 denote the vector of feature and display variables; we detail these variables
 below.
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{ct}$
\end_inset

 is the mean per capita income reported by the Bureau of Economic Analysis
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "BEA2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for county 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in the calendar year that contains quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of quarter of sample indicators, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{ic}$
\end_inset

 is a household-by-county fixed effect.
 Our base regression specification to estimate uniform elasticities that
 do not vary by income is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln s_{it}=-\zeta\ln p_{it}+\xi\ln z_{ct}+\nu\boldsymbol{f}_{it}+\omega_{t}+\mu_{ic}+\varepsilon_{it},\label{eq:ElasticityEstimation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with standard errors clustered by county and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{it}$
\end_inset

 instrumented in a manner we describe below.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As we show in Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ElasticityEstimates_Alt"

\end_inset

, employment status and weekly hours worked are not statistically significantly
 associated with SSB consumption when included in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tab:ElasticityEstimates"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, so we cannot reject weak separability of SSB consumption and labor.
 Thus, it does not matter whether variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{ct}$
\end_inset

 results from non-labor windfalls such as government benefits or from wage
