\begin_layout Subsubsection
Price, Merchandising Conditions, and the Local Price Deviation Instrument
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's SSB price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the average price of the UPCs they usually buy at the stores where they
 usually buy them.
 Specially, define 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ijkt}$
\end_inset

 as the average price that household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 pays for UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 at store 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ijkc}$
\end_inset

 as household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's total purchases of UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 at store 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 while living in county 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, and define 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ic}$
\end_inset

 as household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's total SSB purchases while living in county 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, both measured in liters.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{ijkc}=s_{ijkc}/s_{ic}$
\end_inset

 is the share of household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's SSB liters purchased while in county 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 that are of UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 at store 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's price variable is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{it}=\sum_{k,j}\pi_{ijkc}\ln p_{ijkt}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{it}$
\end_inset

 differs from the average price paid per liter because 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{it}$
\end_inset

 does not vary with the household's quantity choices in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, although the results are very similar if we simply use the average price
 paid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The feature and display variables are constructed analogously, except using
 RMS data.
 Let the 2-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}_{jkt}$
\end_inset

 denote the number of weeks in which UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is featured at RMS store 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, divided by the number of weeks in which feature is observed for that store
 in that quarter, as well as the analogous share of weeks in which UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is observed to be on display at store 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The feature and display variables we use in the household-by-quarter regression
s are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{f}_{it}=\sum_{k,j\in RMS}\pi_{ijkc}\boldsymbol{f}_{jkt}.\label{eq:f}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key challenge in demand estimation is addressing simultaneity bias: omitted
 variables bias generated by a potential correlation between price and unobserve
d demand shifters.
 We address simultaneity bias using a price instrument leveraging two facts
 documented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "DellaVignaGentzkow2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Hitsch2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 First, retail chains vary prices over time in a highly coordinated way
 across their stores: if retailer X is offering Gatorade on sale right now
 in Toledo, it's probably also offering Gatorade on sale in Topeka.
 Second, different chains vary their prices independently of each other
 over time: retailer X's current sale has little relationship to what other
 retailers are doing.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:Uniform-pricing-example"

\end_inset

 illustrates these patterns in more detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct the instrument, define 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{jkw}$
\end_inset

 as the natural log of the price charged at store 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 for UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in week 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 Further define 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{kw}$
\end_inset

 as the national average of natural log price of UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in week 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, unweighted across stores.
 Then, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{krt,-c}$
\end_inset

 denote the unweighted average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{jkw}-\ln p_{kw}$
\end_inset

 at all of retail chain 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

's stores 
\emph on
outside
\emph default
 of county 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 during quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The leave-out construction guarantees that our instrument is not contaminated
 by store-specific responses to local demand shocks, although in practice
 the leave-out construction makes little difference because price variation
 is so coordinated within chains.
 Differencing out the national average price helps remove responses to national-
level demand shocks that might influence the price of the specific UPC 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, which could still be a concern even after we condition on time fixed effects
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 that soak up shocks to overall SSB demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct an instrument for the average SSB price faced by each household,
 we fit the leave-out price deviations 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{krt,-c}$
\end_inset

 to the household's average purchasing patterns.
 Household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's predicted local price deviation in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z_{it}=\sum_{k,j\in RMS}\pi_{ijkc}\ln p_{krt,-c}.\label{eq:Z}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Price deviations 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{krt,-c}$
\end_inset

 are only observed at RMS stores, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{it}$
\end_inset

 sums only over purchases at RMS stores; approximately 
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../../Output/Analysis/NumbersForText/RMSPurchaseShare.tex"

\end_inset

percent of SSB purchases are at RMS chains.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{ijkc}$
\end_inset

 is the purchase share across all SSB purchases (at both RMS and non-RMS
 stores), each household's quantity-weighted prices paid 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{it}$
\end_inset

 should vary approximately one-for-one with 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{it}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exclusion restriction is that the local price instrument 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{it}$
\end_inset

 is uncorrelated with demand shifters 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{it}$
\end_inset

, conditional on the set of controls in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ElasticityEstimation"

\end_inset

.
 The economic content of this assumption is that when retail chains vary
 prices across weeks and quarters, they do not observe and respond to 
\emph on
chain-specific
\emph default
 demand shocks.
 One threat to this assumption would be price cuts coordinated with retailer-spe
cific advertising, but retailers do little advertising beyond the newspaper
 and online ads and coupons that are already captured by RMS feature variable
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DellaVignaGentzkow2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, we show below that the estimates are largely unaffected by
 alternative instrument constructions and fixed effect controls that address
 other types of regional and city-specific demand shocks.
\end_layout

