\begin_layout Subsubsection
Substitution to Untaxed Sin Goods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:multiple"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we derived the optimal SSB tax when complement or substitute sin goods
 are not taxed.
 A key statistic for that formula is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, the share of SSB expenditures that are reallocated to other sin goods
 in response to an SSB tax increase.
 We now estimate that statistic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To keep the scope manageable, we first define a set of goods that are both
 unhealthy and plausible substitutes or complements to SSBs.
 We consider all Nielsen product modules averaging more than 15 percent
 sugar content by weight.
 This definition includes everything from the highest-sugar modules (sugar,
 syrups, sweeteners, etc.) down to moderate-sugar modules such as sauces
 (pickle relish, ketchup, etc.) and crackers (graham crackers, wafers, etc.).
 We add diet drinks, because these are likely substitutes even though the
 health harms are uncertain.
 We also add alcohol and cigarettes, which could be substitutes or complements
 to sugary drinks if consumers think of them together as a class of tempting
 pleasures.
 We group these into 12 groups, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and construct household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's grams purchased in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{nit}$
\end_inset

, as well as price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{nit}$
\end_inset

, instrument 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{nit}$
\end_inset

, and feature and display 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}_{nit}$
\end_inset

 analogous to the SSB variables described above.
 We estimate the following regression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln r_{nit}=\tilde{\zeta}\ln p_{it}+\zeta_{n}\ln p_{nit}+\tilde{\xi}\ln z_{ct}+\nu\boldsymbol{f}_{it}+\nu_{n}\boldsymbol{f}_{nit}+\omega_{t}+\mu_{ic}+\varepsilon_{it},\label{eq:SubstitutionPatterns}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

instrumenting for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{it}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p_{nit}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{it}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{nit}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Substitution"

\end_inset

 presents results.
 The first three columns present substitute beverages, the next eight columns
 present substitute foods, and the final column of the bottom panel presents
 tobacco.
 The estimated own-price elasticities 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\zeta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 are in a reasonable range between 0.5 and 2.
 Unsurprisingly, we find that SSBs and diet drinks are substitutes.
 Only one of the other 11 groups has a statistically significant cross-price
 elasticity.
 The average of the 12 cross-price elasticities is a statistically insignificant
 
\begin_inset Formula $\input{../../Output/Analysis/NumbersForText/MeanSubElastb.tex}$
\end_inset

, suggesting that if anything, these other goods are slight complements
 on average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these estimates, we construct an estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\varphi}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each household and get the population average, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\varphi}\approx\input{../../Output/Analysis/NumbersForText/varphi1.tex}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Specifically, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $dt=dp_{it}$
\end_inset

 and construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\frac{dx_{nit}}{dt}}=\hat{\zeta}_{n}\frac{x_{nit}p_{nit}}{p_{it}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\frac{dx_{si}}{dt}}=\hat{\zeta}_{i}s_{it}$
\end_inset

 , and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\varphi}_{it}=-\frac{\sum_{n}\widehat{\frac{dx_{nit}}{dt}}}{\widehat{\frac{dx_{s}}{dt}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Because the health effects of diet drinks are under debate in the public
 health literature, we construct a second 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 excluding diet drinks (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\varphi}\approx\input{../../Output/Analysis/NumbersForText/varphi2.tex}$
\end_inset

).
 Finally, because diet drinks are the most natural substitute to sugary
 drinks, while the other estimates may simply be imprecise zeros, we construct
