\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Counterfactual Normative Consumer Estimation Strategy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Model"

\end_inset

, we defined bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 as the compensated price cut that would induce the counterfactual normative
 self to consume as much of the sin good as the actual biased self.
 Our 
\emph on
counterfactual normative consumer
\emph default
 empirical strategy directly implements this definition, using an approach
 that builds on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bronnenberg-Dube-Gentzkow-Shapiro-2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Handel2015a"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and other work.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bartels1996"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cutler2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Handel2015a"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Johnson2016"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Levitt2008"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 similarly compare informed to uninformed agents to identify the effects
 of imperfect information.
 All of these papers require the same identifying assumption: that preferences
 are conditionally uncorrelated with measures of informedness.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bronnenberg-Dube-Gentzkow-Shapiro-2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 show that sophisticated shoppers—in their application, doctors and pharmacists—
are more likely to buy generic instead of branded drugs, and use this to
 infer that unsophisticated shoppers are making mistakes by not buying generics.
 The 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bronnenberg-Dube-Gentzkow-Shapiro-2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 identifying assumptions may initially seem more plausible because branded
 vs.
 generic drugs are close substitutes, while consumer tastes for SSBs vary
 substantially.
 But if generic drugs are perfect substitutes, then the sophisticated shoppers'
 decisions are not needed to identify consumer mistakes.
 The reason to study sophisticated shoppers is to avoid the assumption that
 generics are perfect substitutes, at which point one must maintain the
 same assumption that sophisticated and unsophisticated shoppers do not
 have heterogeneous preferences for the attributes that differentiate branded
 drugs.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The process is to use surveys to elicit proxies of bias, estimate the relations
hip between bias proxies and quantity consumed, use that relationship to
 predict the counterfactual quantity that would be consumed if consumers
 instead maximized normative utility, and finally transform the quantity
 difference into dollar units using the price elasticity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formalize the approach, recall that money-metric bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is defined to satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $s(p,y,\theta)=s^{V}(p-\gamma,y-s\gamma,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 We log-linearize this equation as described in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:log linearization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and we now use an 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 subscript for each household in the data, recognizing that each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 maps to a 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,y,\theta)$
\end_inset

 triple.
 This gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln s_{i}=\ln s_{i}^{V}+\zeta_{i}^{c}\gamma_{i}/p_{i},\label{eq:log-linearization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln s_{i}^{V}$
\end_inset

 denotes the log of the quantity that household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 would consume in the absence of bias, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 are observed in the Homescan data, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{i}^{c}$
\end_inset

 is the compensated price elasticity of demand, which we obtain from the
 Slutsky equation using our estimates of the uncompensated price elasticity
 and income effects.
 As an example, imagine that bias increases quantity demanded by 15% and
 that the compensated demand elasticity is 1.5.
 Then the impact of bias on consumption is the same as a 10% price reduction:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}=p_{i}\cdot15\%/1.5=10\%\cdot p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{i}=[b_{ki},b_{si}]$
\end_inset

 denote a vector of indices measuring household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's bias: nutrition knowledge 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{ki}$
\end_inset

 and self-control 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{si}$
\end_inset

, as measured in the PanelViews survey.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}^{V}=[b_{k}^{V},b_{s}^{V}]$
\end_inset

 denote the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}$
\end_inset

 for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 consumer that maximizes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of preferences (beverage tastes and health preferences) measured
 in the PanelViews survey, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of household characteristics introduced in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:DescriptiveStatistics"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a county fixed effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that a household's SSB purchases depend on the average biases,
 preferences, and demographics of all (one or two) household heads.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:HMSPrimShopBiasEffects"

\end_inset

 presents estimates under the alternative assumption that a household's
 SSB purchases depend on the biases and preferences of the primary shopper
 only.
 The pattern of results is very similar, but the coefficient estimates and
 resulting bias magnitudes are attenuated by about 15 percent.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For two-head households, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{si}$
\end_inset

 is the average of the primary shopper's self-control assessments for herself
 and the other head.
 In two-head households where only one head responded, we impute household
 average nutrition knowledge 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{ki}$
\end_inset

 and preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 based on the observed head's bias proxies and preferences; see Appendix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:MeasurementError"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our empirical strategy for estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 requires the following three assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Normative consumers: 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}^{V}=\mathbb{E}[b_{ki}|dietitian,nutritionist],\ b_{s}^{V}=1.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For nutrition knowledge, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}^{V}$
\end_inset

 equal to the average nutrition knowledge score of the 24 dietitians and
 nutritionists in the PanelViews survey, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\input{../../Output/Analysis/NumbersForText/NutritionistAverageKnowledge.tex}$
\end_inset

.
 For self-control, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{s}^{V}=1$
\end_inset

: normative consumers are those for whom 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

not at all
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the correct response to the statement, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I drink soda pop or other sugar-sweetened beverages more often than I should.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assump:Linearity"

\end_inset

Linearity: 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{i}^{c}\gamma_{i}/p_{i}=\boldsymbol{\tau}\cdot(\boldsymbol{b}^{V}-\boldsymbol{b}_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\tau}$
\end_inset

 comprises two parameters scaling the effects of nutrition knowledge and
 self-control.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our data, linearity is a realistic assumption, as demonstrated in Appendix
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Linearity"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Linearity is also theoretically plausible, as it results from any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

structural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 behavioral model in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 scales the share of costs that are misperceived—for example, a 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta,\delta$
\end_inset

 model in which consumers downweight future health effects and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To show the final equation in this footnote, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}=\left(1-\frac{b_{i}}{b^{V}}\right)h=\frac{b^{V}-b_{i}}{b^{V}}h$
\end_inset

, so linearity implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{b^{V}-b_{i}}{b^{V}}h\frac{\zeta^{c}}{p_{i}}=\tau(b^{V}-b_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $(b^{V}-b_{i})$
\end_inset

 shows that this holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\frac{h\zeta^{c}}{b^{V}p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assump:Unconfoundedness"

\end_inset

Unconfoundedness: 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{i}\bot(\ln s_{i}^{V}|\boldsymbol{a}_{i},\boldsymbol{x}_{i},\mu_{c})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In words, bias is conditionally independent of normative consumption.
 While such unconfoundedness assumptions are often unrealistic, this is
 more plausible in our setting because of our tailor-made survey measures
 of beverage tastes and health preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:log-linearization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and Assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assump:Linearity"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assump:Unconfoundedness"

\end_inset

 imply our estimating equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln(s_{i}+1)=\boldsymbol{\tau}\boldsymbol{b}_{i}+\beta_{a}\boldsymbol{a}_{i}+\beta_{x}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}+\mu_{c}+\varepsilon_{i}.\label{eq:BiasEffects}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We add 1 to SSB purchases before taking the natural log so as to include
 households with zero purchases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting our parameter estimates into Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:log-linearization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and Assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assump:Linearity"

\end_inset

, we obtain estimates of counterfactual normative consumption and money-metric
 bias:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\log\hat{s}_{i}^{V} & =\log s_{i}-\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}(\boldsymbol{b}^{V}-\hat{\boldsymbol{b}}_{i})\label{eq:NormativeConsumption}\\
\hat{\gamma}_{i} & =\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}(\boldsymbol{b}^{V}-\hat{\boldsymbol{b}}_{i})p_{i}/\hat{\zeta}_{i}^{c}.\label{eq:gamma_hat}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

