LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Bias_Consumption"

\end_inset

, both nutrition knowledge and self-control are highly conditionally associated
 with lower SSB purchases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are at least three important reasons to be concerned about this empirical
 strategy, some of which can be partially addressed in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BiasEffects"

\end_inset

.
 First, a central concern is our unconfoundedness assumption.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An alternative approach that would identify the causal effect of nutrition
 knowledge would be to run an information provision field experiment, as
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Allcott2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 or the nutrition education interventions reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Vargas2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, this is also an imperfect way to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, as it requires the assumption that the intervention is sufficiently comprehens
ive and well-understood to remove all bias from the treatment group.
 Furthermore, such experiments in practice involve additional challenges
 around demand effects and external validity.
 The finding in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Vargas2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that nutrition information interventions have limited effects could be
 because lack of nutrition knowledge has little impact on purchases, or
 it could be because the interventions were incomplete or easily forgotten.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Our demographics and taste variables are potentially noisy and incomplete
 measures of normatively valid preferences, meaning that unobserved preferences
 might bias the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

.
 To explore this, columns 2-4 illustrate coefficient movement: how the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 estimates change with the exclusion of different controls.
 Preferences, income, and education are correlated with both SSB purchases
 and bias proxies, so it is unsurprising that their exclusion increases
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 in column 2 relative to the primary estimates in column 1.
 Other demographics (age, race, the presence of children, household size,
 employment status, and weekly work hours) and county indicators, however,
 have relatively little effect on 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 in columns 3 and 4.
 This limited coefficient movement in columns 3 and 4 is consistent with
 the idea that unobservables also have limited impacts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

, although this is certainly not dispositive due to the low 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 values 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Oster2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second concern is measurement error in the self-control variable.
 For example, survey respondents with different incomes and SSB demands
 might not interpret the response categories (not at all, mostly, etc.) in
 the same way, as highlighted in a related setting by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BondLang2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As another example, respondents might have interpreted the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more often than I should
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 phrasing of the question in different ways that don't necessarily reflect
 bias, e.g.
 that they are optimizing but would aspire to something different in the
 absence of financial or other constraints.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Bias_Interactions"

\end_inset

 presents additional estimates including an interaction term between knowledge
 and self-control.
 This interaction term is highly significant, perhaps because it takes knowledge
 of health damages to believe that one 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

should
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 consume less.
 Including this interaction in the model, however, does not materially change
 the estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In general, measurement error could bias our estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 up or down.
 One natural model is a type of classical measurement error: noise is uncorrelat
ed with SSB purchases, uncorrelated with income, and uncorrelated across
 different survey responses within the same household.
 In this model, our estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tau}$
\end_inset

 for self-control in column 1 would attenuated toward zero, but we can recover
 unbiased estimates by instrumenting for self-control.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We address measurement error through several sensitivity analyses.
 First, we construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 by halving or doubling the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tau}$
\end_inset

 coefficient on self-control from column 1.
 Second, column 5 of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BiasEffects"

\end_inset

 simply omits the self-control variable, allowing an estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 that depends only on nutrition knowledge.
 Because knowledge and self-control are positively correlated, the nutrition
 knowledge coefficient is stronger in this column.
 Third, we instrument for self-control using the repeated measurements in
 the households where two heads responded to the PanelViews survey, using
 a two-sample two-stage least squares procedure detailed in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:MeasurementError"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Column 6 presents results.
 Comparing to column 1, we see that the measurement error correction addresses
 what would otherwise be substantial attenuation bias in the self-control
 coefficient.
 We use the results in this column to construct yet another alternative
 estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, which is unbiased under classical measurement error.
 Positive (negative) correlation in measurement error across household heads
 would imply that the column 6 estimates are lower (upper) bounds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A final important concern with the empirical strategy is that we assume
 that our survey measures fully capture the only types of biases that affect
 SSB consumption.
 In reality, our measures may be incomplete measures of all types of imperfect
 knowledge and self-control that could affect SSB consumption.
 Furthermore, if other biases increase SSB consumption—for example, projection
 bias or inattention to health harms—then we could understate the optimal
 SSB tax.
 We chose these two biases and these specific survey questions because we
 thought that these best reflected the most relevant and plausible sources
 of bias.
\end_layout

