\begin_layout Standard
We import an externality estimate from outside sources.
 Using epidemiological simulation models, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wang2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 estimate that one ounce of soda consumption increases health care costs
 by an average of approximately one cent per ounce.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Yong2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 estimate that for people with employer-provided insurance, about 15 percent
 of health costs are borne by the individual, while 85 percent are covered
 by insurance.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cawley2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 estimate that 88 percent of the total medical costs of obesity are borne
 by third parties, and obesity is one of the primary diseases thought to
 be caused by SSB consumption.
 Accordingly, we approximate the health system externality at 
\begin_inset Formula $e\approx0.85$
\end_inset

 cents per ounce.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two caveats to this calculation.
 First, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bhattacharya2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

