\begin_layout Section
Computing the Optimal Sugar-Sweetened Beverage Tax
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Computation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now combine the theoretical results from Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Model"

\end_inset

 with the empirical estimates from Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimation"

\end_inset

 to compute the optimal nationwide tax on SSBs.
 We compute the optimal tax across a range of specifications, under two
 different assumptions about the income tax.
 First, we compute the optimal SSB tax assuming the income tax is held fixed
 at the current status quo in the U.S., using Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:FixedIncomeTax"

\end_inset

.
 Second, we compute the optimal SSB tax assuming the income tax is also
 reformed to be optimal, using Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:t opt 1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:general opt tax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These computations require an assumption about inequality aversion.
 We employ a schedule of social marginal welfare weights common in the optimal
 taxation literature (see, for example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Saez2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{US}^{-\nu}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{US}$
\end_inset

 is post-tax income in the U.S., and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is a parameter which governs the strength of inequality aversion.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=1$
\end_inset

 as our baseline, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0.25$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=4$
\end_inset

 as our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weak
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

strong
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 redistributive preferences, respectively.
 We also report optimal taxes computed under the assumption that redistributive
 preferences rationalize the observed U.S.
 income tax.
 Calibrations of the status quo U.S.
 income distribution and income tax are drawn from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Piketty2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

; see Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:SimCalibrations"

\end_inset

 for details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sufficient statistics formulas for the optimal tax depend on a number
 of statistics, as well as their covariances with welfare weights.
 These statistics are reported in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ManualTable"

\end_inset

.
 Panel (a) presents estimates of the key population-level statistics estimated
 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, while Panel (b) presents estimates of statistics within each Homescan
 income bin.
 Details of these calculations are reported in the table notes for Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ManualTable"

\end_inset

.
 We compute the sufficient statistics involving covariances using the discrete
 covariance formula reported in the table notes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:taxComputation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows how these statistics enter the theoretical formula from Proposition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:FixedIncomeTax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the optimal sin tax under a fixed income tax—this represents our baseline
 calculation of the optimal SSB tax, which is 
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../../Output/Simulations/NumbersForText/optTaxbaseline.tex"

\end_inset

cents per ounce.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
t & \approx\frac{\bar{\gamma}(1+\sigma)+e-\frac{p}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}\left(Cov\left[g(z),s(z)\right]+\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{T'(z(\theta))}{1-T'(z(\theta))}\zeta_{z}(\theta)s(\theta)\xi(\theta)\right]\right)}{1+\frac{1}{\bar{s}\bar{\zeta}^{c}}\left(Cov\left[g(z),s(z)\right]+\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{T'(z(\theta))}{1-T'(z(\theta))}\zeta_{z}(\theta)s(\theta)\xi(\theta)\right]\right)},\nonumber \\
