\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:general opt tax"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 therefore implies an optimal sin tax of 
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../../Output/Simulations/NumbersForText/optTaxOptIncTaxbaseline.tex"

\end_inset

cents per ounce.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal SSB tax is higher under the status quo income tax than under
 the optimal income tax because under our assumed welfare weights, status
 quo marginal income tax rates are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

too low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relative to the optimum.
 Since SSB taxes distort labor supply downward when SSBs are a normal good,
 they create a negative fiscal externality through the income tax.
 That negative fiscal externality is much larger under the optimal income
 tax than under the status quo because the marginal income tax rates of
 the optimal income tax are much larges than those of the status quo.
 Consequently, the optimal SSB tax is lower under the optimal income tax.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These estimates of the optimal SSB tax are reported in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:OptTaxResults"

\end_inset

, along with calculations under several alternative assumptions that we
 now summarize.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second row of Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:OptTaxResults"

\end_inset

 reports the optimal tax estimated using self-reported SSB consumption from
 our PanelViews survey, rather than data captured by Homescan.
 This specification results in a higher optimal SSB tax of 
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../../Output/Simulations/NumbersForText/optTaxselfReports.tex"

\end_inset

cents per ounce.
 (All other rows use the Homescan data used for the baseline calculation.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next three rows consider alternative assumptions about the policymaker's
 preference for redistribution.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Pigouvian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 specification reports the optimal tax in the absence of any inequality
