\begin_layout Standard
We define labor supply responses to include any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

circularities
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 due to the curvature of the income tax function, which is assumed to be
 differentiable.
 Thus, following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jacquet2014"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, we define a tax function 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 which has been locally perturbed around the income level 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0}$
\end_inset

 by raising the marginal tax rate by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and reducing the tax level by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{T}(z;z_{0},\tau,\nu):=T(z)+\tau(z-z_{0})-\nu.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}(\theta)$
\end_inset

 denote a type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

's choice of earnings under the status quo income tax 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}(\theta;\tau,\nu$
\end_inset

) denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

's choice of earnings under the perturbed income tax 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}(z;z^{*}(\theta),\tau,\nu)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the compensated elasticity of taxable income is defined in terms of
 the response of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\nu=0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\zeta_{z}^{c}(\theta):=\left(-\left.\frac{\partial\hat{z}(\theta;\tau,0)}{\partial\tau}\right|_{\tau=0}\right)\frac{1-T'(z^{*}(\theta))}{z^{*}(\theta)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The income tax is similarly defined in terms of the response of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 to a tax credit 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (this statistic will be nonpositive if leisure is a non-inferior good):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{z}(\theta):=\left(\left.\frac{\partial\hat{z}(\theta;0,\nu)}{\partial\nu}\right|_{\nu=0}\right)\left(1-T'(z^{*}(\theta))\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These definitions are comparable to those in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Saez2001"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, except that they include circularities and thus permit a representation
 of the optimal income tax in terms of the actual earnings density, rather
 than the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

virtual density
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 employed in that paper.
 
\end_layout

