\begin_layout Subsection
Assessment of Strengths and Weaknesses
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:Empirical_Assessment"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this appendix, we assess the strengths and weaknesses of the empirical
 strategies employed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Identifying the price elasticity of demand.

\series default
 Our instrumental variables approach has advantages relative to alternative
 methods of identifying price elasticity.
 One alternative is to use recent SSB tax changes in U.S.
 cities as an instrument.
 This would require the assumption that no other factors affected SSB demand
 at the time the SSB tax was implemented.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ReesJones2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 document one potential violation of this assumption: local public debates
 about sin taxes also affect demand, even in cities where prices never changed
 because the tax never went into effect.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In our theory model, a tax affects demand only through prices, not through
 signaling or public awareness.
 The tax elasticity of demand estimated in these papers would be one crucial
 input into a richer model.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Furthermore, because there have been only a small handful of city-level
 SSB taxes implemented in the U.S., this approach will tend to deliver less
 precise estimates for the foreseeable future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second alternative is to use pricing instruments such as those introduced
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hausman1996"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Nevo2001"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, who instrument for the price of a product at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 using the average price of that product in all other cities.
 This requires the assumption that time-varying demand shocks for a given
 product are uncorrelated across cities, which assumes away possibilities
 such as national advertising campaigns.
 Our instrument also delivers more power, because it exploits the extensive
 idiosyncratic chain-specific price variation instead of the more limited
 variation in national average prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A third alternative is to regress quantities on prices without an instrument,
 as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Dubois2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Tiffin2014"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zhen2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and others.
 With our particular vector of controls, Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ElasticityEstimates_Alt"

\end_inset

 shows that the OLS estimates understate price elasticity by about a factor
 of two, which is suggestive of either a standard simultaneity bias or measureme
nt error in prices.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Dubois2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and the other papers adopting this approach have different data and control
 strategies, so their estimates certainly need not be biased in this same
 way.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Long-run versus short-run elasticities
\series default
.
 Because the commodity taxes and income taxes we model are long-lasting,
 we ideally want long-run elasticities to calibrate optimal taxes.
 In the absence of plausibly exogenous long-run price and income variation,
 we estimate the price and income elasticities of demand for SSBs using
 quarterly prices and annual income.
 To the extent that there is habit formation in SSB consumption, this variation
 would cause us to understate elasticities.
 In Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:PriceAndIncomeElasticity_IVLag"

\end_inset

, we see no impact of lagged quarterly prices on current consumption, although
 this does not rule out habit formation over a longer time horizon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Measuring SSB consumption with scanner data vs.
 self-reports.

\series default
 While purchase data are incomplete for the reasons discussed in the paper,
 self-reported intake data have other limitations that could bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 up or down.
 For example, self-reports of consumption and self-control could both suffer
 from recency or salience bias: the judgments may be constructed based on
 only the most recent or salient consumption episodes.
 The resulting correlated measurement error would generate an upward-biased
 relationship between self-reported consumption and self-control.
 Additionally, social desirability bias could cause people with more health
 knowledge or less perceived self-control to under-report consumption, which
 could bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 either up or down.
 Using scanner-based purchase data avoids these potential problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Homescan's incomplete consumption measures could also affect our price elasticit
y estimate.
 If households substitute between scanned and non-scanned SSBs, for example
 by buying less soda at a restaurant when grocery store prices are lower,
 the estimated price elasticity of scanned purchases will likely overstate
 the true SSB price elasticity.
 We explore the policy implications of a more inelastic alternative elasticity
 assumption in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Computation"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Comparison to other bias measurement approaches.

\series default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BernheimTaubinsky"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Mullainathan2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and others review the possible approaches to estimating biases for public
 policy applications.
 We briefly discuss the merits of these other approaches in the context
 of SSB consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One approach is to calibrate or estimate models of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bias
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 parameters.
 For example, in the older working paper version of this paper, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LockwoodandTaubinsky2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 assume that all bias is a consequence of present bias, and use evidence
 from behavioral economics and public health to calibrate a present bias
 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and a marginal health cost parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to arrive to an estimate of bias 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=(1-\beta)h$
\end_inset

.
 This strategy rests on many assumptions: that measures of present bias
 from laboratory experiments about effort or money can be extrapolated to
 a representative population and to the alternate domain of SSB consumption;
 that the measures of marginal health costs (obtained from mostly correlational
 public health studies) are accurate and independent of the types of SSBs
 purchased; and that bias is homogeneous across the population; and that
 there are no biases besides present bias.
 Preference reversal experiments with groceries such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Sadoff2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 could be used to provide qualitative within-domain evidence of present
 bias, but such designs do not deliver money-metric bias estimates and would
 be prohibitively difficult to carry out on a nationally representative
 sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mistakes arising from misinformation could also be measured using survey-elicite
d beliefs.
 This approach of eliciting beliefs about health costs is similar in spirit
 to our approach, but unlike our approach requires strong assumptions about
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 marginal health costs as well as reasonably strong structural assumptions
 about how health costs affect decision and normative utility.
 Furthermore, consumers may or may not act on the beliefs that they state
 in a survey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, one might estimate informational and attentional biases through
 an information provision field experiment, as we discuss in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:BiasEffects"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This strategy requires the assumption that the information provided fully
 debiases the information treatment group, which could be unrealistic in
 the case of complex information around nutrition and health.
 Our nutrition knowledge scores capture information gathered over a long
 period, which would probably be prohibitively difficult to induce experimentall
y.
 Moreover, if the dependent variable reflects naturally-occurring decisions
 such as those in Homescan, this strategy would also require that the informatio
n provision is processed by all consumers, is remembered, and is salient
 at the time of choice—conditions that seem implausible outside a controlled,
 online shopping experiment as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Allcott2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 At the same time, a controlled online shopping experiment would not lead
 to plausible estimates of demand curves (and therefore bias) in our context,
 because SSBs are easy to purchase and these outside options would be perfect
 substitutes for the products in the experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In sum, while our approach requires a strong unconfoundedness assumption
 and has other weaknesses, other possible approaches to estimating bias
 involve arguably stronger assumptions and are, in our view, even more likely
 to suffer from confounds.
 Moreover, and in contrast to the requirements of some other approaches,
 the dataset we use to estimate demand elasticities is essentially the same
 one we use for estimating bias—a key advantage for internal consistency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Deriving the Estimating Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:DerivingEstimatingEquations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this appendix we derive the estimating equations used in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to estimate both the elasticities and the bias.
 We do this in two ways.
 First, we show that the estimating equations can be derived by log-linearizing
 the general utility function.
 This approach is in line with the sufficient statistics approach of much
 of the optimal tax literature, which considers only local variation of
 the parameters.
 Although the elasticities are not guaranteed to be globally constant, they
 are locally constant.
 The key assumption assumption for the log-linearized approximation to be
 a good one is that the empirical variation in prices and incomes that we
 consider is not too big.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our second approach, we show that our estimating equation can be derived
 from a CES utility function, using only the approximation that expenditures
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are a negligibly small share of income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Log-linearization to Derive Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:log-linearization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:log linearization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that bias is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\theta,z,y,p)=s^{V}(\theta,z,y-\gamma s^{V},p-\gamma)$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the tuples 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta,z,y,p)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\bar{x}}=(\theta,\bar{z},y,\bar{p})$
\end_inset

.
 We assumed terms of order two or higher (with respect to price, bias, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

) are negligible.
 Formally, we assume that for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}+n_{2}+n_{3}=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}\ln s^{V}}{(d\ln z)^{n_{1}}(d\ln y)^{n_{2}}(d\ln p)^{n_{3}}}\Bigr|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{\bar{x}}}(\ln(z_{t}/z))^{n_{1}}(\gamma s^{V}/y)^{n_{2}}(1-p/\bar{p}+\gamma/\bar{p})^{n_{3}}$
\end_inset

 is negligible, which also implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}\ln s^{V}}{(d\ln z)^{n_{1}}(d\ln y)^{n_{2}}(d\ln p)^{n_{3}}}\Bigr|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{\bar{x}}}(\ln(z_{t}/z))^{n_{1}}(\ln(1-\gamma s^{V}/y))^{n_{2}}(\ln(p/\bar{p}-\gamma/\bar{p}))^{n_{3}}$
\end_inset

 is negligible.
 We now consider an expansion of normative consumption around the average
 price 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{p}$
\end_inset

 and average income 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \ln s(\theta,z_{t},y,p)-\ln s^{V}(\theta,\bar{z},y,\bar{p})\\
 & =\ln s^{V}(\theta,z_{t},y-\gamma s^{V},p-\gamma)-\ln s^{V}(\theta,\bar{z},y,\bar{p})\\
 & \approx\frac{d\ln s^{V}}{d\ln z}\Bigr|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{\bar{x}}}(\ln z_{t}-\ln\bar{z})+\frac{d\ln s^{V}}{d\ln y}\Bigr|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{\bar{x}}}(\ln(1-\gamma s^{V}/y))+\frac{d\ln s^{V}}{d\ln p}\Bigr|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{\bar{x}}}(\ln(p/\bar{p}-\gamma/\bar{p})))\\
 & =\frac{d\ln s}{d\ln z}(\ln z_{t}-\ln\bar{z})+\frac{d\ln s^{V}}{d\ln y}(\ln(1-\gamma s^{V}/y))+\frac{d\ln s^{V}}{d\ln p}(\ln(p/\bar{p}-\gamma/\bar{p}))\\
 & \approx\xi\ln(z_{t}/\bar{z})-\frac{ds^{V}}{dy}\cdot\frac{y}{s}\cdot\frac{\gamma s}{y}-\zeta^{V}\ln(p/\bar{p})+\zeta^{V}\frac{\gamma}{\bar{p}}\\
 & =\xi\ln(z_{t})-\zeta\ln p-\bar{p}\frac{ds^{V}}{dy}\frac{\gamma}{\bar{p}}+\zeta^{V}\frac{\gamma}{\bar{p}}+\zeta^{V}\ln\bar{p}-\xi\ln(\bar{z})\\
 & =\xi\ln(z_{t}/\bar{z})-\zeta\ln(p/\bar{p})+\zeta^{c,V}\frac{\gamma}{\bar{p}}+\zeta\ln\bar{p}-\xi\ln(\bar{z})
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\ln\bar{p}-\xi\ln\bar{z}$
\end_inset

