\begin_layout Standard
Because SSBs are storable, past prices and merchandising conditions that
 affect past purchases could in theory affect current stockpiles and thus
 current purchases.
 To address this, we estimate a version of Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ElasticityEstimation"

\end_inset

 that includes lags of the price and merchandising condition variables.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 index quarterly lags, we estimate the following regression: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln s_{it}=\sum_{l=0}^{L}\zeta_{l}\ln p_{i,t-l}+\sum_{l=0}^{L}\nu_{l}\boldsymbol{f}_{i,t-l}+\xi\ln z_{ct}+\omega_{t}+\mu_{ic}+\varepsilon_{it},\label{eq:ElasticityEstimation-Lags}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with standard errors clustered by county.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:PriceAndIncomeElasticity_First"

\end_inset

, we find that the local price IV 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{it}$
\end_inset

 is a powerful predictor of price paid in quarter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 but is not strongly conditionally correlated with prices paid in the quarters
 before and after.
 This implies that we have strong first stages and do not have large serial
 autocorrelation problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A standard approach to determining the optimal number of lags in a distributed
 lag model is to choose the specification that minimizes the Aikake Information
 Criterion (AIC) or Bayesian Information Criteria (BIC).
 In essence, these criteria find the specification that best predicts purchases
 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 As shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:PriceAndIncomeElasticity_IVLag"

\end_inset

, the specification that minimizes AIC and BIC is to set 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 to include only contemporaneous quarter prices.
 Furthermore, the coefficients on lagged prices in the table are all statistical
ly zero, implying no statistically detectable stockpiling of SSBs from quarter
 to quarter.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This result is consistent with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "DellaVignaGentzkow2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, who find that stores offering lower prices in a given week see little
 decrease in sales in future weeks and months, even for relatively storable
 goods.
 Prior work highlighting household stockpiling (e.g.
 Hendel and Nevo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "HendelNevoEcma,HendelNevoRAND,HendelNevo2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wang2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) typically uses weekly purchase data, and stockpiling is naturally more
 relevant across weeks than across quarters.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For these reasons, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

 when estimating demand in the body of the paper, thereby including only
 contemporaneous prices and merchandising conditions.
\end_layout

