\begin_layout Section
Measurement Error Correction for Bias Estimation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:MeasurementError"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are measured imperfectly, for two reasons.
 First, household head average biases and preferences are unobserved for
 two-head households in which only one head responded to the survey.
 Second, the PanelViews survey delivers bias 
\emph on
proxies
\emph default
 that may contain measurement error.
 This appendix details how we address these issues.
 For this appendix, we now distinguish between bias, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and the bias 
\emph on
proxies
\emph default
 measured in the PanelViews survey, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observed bias proxies are as follows.
 For two-head households, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{1si}$
\end_inset

 is the average of the primary shopper's self-control assessments for herself
 and the other head, and in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../../Output/Analysis/NumbersForText/PanelViews2RespondentHouseholds.tex"

\end_inset

households where both heads responded, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{2si}$
\end_inset

 is the analogous average constructed from the other head's responses.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bronnenberg-Dube-Gentzkow-Shapiro-2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 in defining each household's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

primary shopper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by selecting the survey respondent who makes the majority of the grocery
 purchase decisions, then the female, then the older person, until we arrive
 at a single primary shopper in each household.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In one-head households, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{1si}$
\end_inset

 is simply the household head's self-control assessment for herself.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{1ki}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{2ki}$
\end_inset

 are the nutrition knowledge scores for the primary shopper and other head,
 if observed, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{ki}$
\end_inset

 is the household head average nutrition knowledge score.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We make two additional assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assump:MeasurementError"

\end_inset

Measurement error in self-control: For self-control, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{1si}=b_{si}+\nu_{1si}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{2si}=b_{si}+\nu_{2si}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nu_{1si},\nu_{2si})\bot b_{si}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu{}_{1si}\bot\nu{}_{2si}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu{}_{1si}$
\end_inset

 does not depend on whether the household has one or two heads and on whether
 one or both heads responded to the survey.
 We assume no measurement error in nutrition knowledge.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The classical measurement error assumption for self-control could be violated
 in reality, for example if spouses are both unaware of biases, or if one
 spouse's preferences (e.g.
 that the other spouse would lose weight) both cause them to respond that
 the other spouse 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

should
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 drink fewer SSBs and affect the household's overall SSB purchases.
 It is reasonable to make the approximation that nutrition knowledge is
 measured without error, because the General Nutrition Knowledge Questionnaire
 is a many-question scale with high sensitivity to change and construct
 validity and a high test-retest reliability of 0.89 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kliemann2016"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assump:missing households"

\end_inset

Missing at random: in two-head households, biases and preferences are not
 correlated with whether both heads responded to the survey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address non-response in two-head households where only one head responded,
 we impute household average nutrition knowledge nutrition knowledge 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{ki}$
\end_inset

 and preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 based on the observed head's bias proxies and preferences.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Specifically, for each variable 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{ki}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

, we impute with the predictions from a regression of household average
 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{c}$
\end_inset

, and the primary shopper's 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{ki}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

, in the sample of two-head households where both heads responded.
 Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Bias_Imputation"

\end_inset

 presents these regressions.
 There is little uncertainty in these imputations: the adjusted 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

's are around 0.7 to 0.8.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We use these imputations in the primary estimates in the body of the paper
 as well.
 For this appendix, we denote household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's observed or imputed nutrition knowledge and preferences as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{b}}_{ki}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{a}}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 To address measurement error in self-control, we use two-sample two-stage
 least squares (2SLS).
 In the first stage, we regress 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{2si}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{1si}$
\end_inset

 and the other covariates from Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:BiasEffects"

\end_inset

 in the subset of households with two survey respondents, and we construct
 fitted values 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{b}}_{2si}$
\end_inset

 for all households.
 Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Bias_FirstStage"

\end_inset

 presents this first stage regression.
 For the second stage, we estimate Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:BiasEffects"

\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{\boldsymbol{b}}}_{i}=[\tilde{b}_{ki},\hat{\tilde{b}}_{2si}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{a}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We calculate standard errors using the procedure of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ChodorowReich2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which accounts for heteroskedasticity and the interdependence between
 the first- and second-stage samples.
 Assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "assump:MeasurementError"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "assump:missing households"

\end_inset

 guarantee that the imputation and measurement error correction procedures
 yield consistent estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\tau}$
\end_inset

 in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:BiasEffects"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our paper is one of only a small number to correct for measurement error
