\begin_layout Standard
We jointly calibrate the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $a(c)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\theta)$
\end_inset

 nonparametrically to match both the level of SSB consumption (across the
 income distribution) and the estimated SSB income elasticity, using the
 following procedure.
 We first assume 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(c)=0$
\end_inset

, and we calibrate the product 
\begin_inset Formula $a(c)b(\theta)$
\end_inset

 at each point in the income distribution—without yet worrying about the
 decomposition into separate terms—to match the observed schedule of SSB
 consumption via the first-order condition for SSB consumption.
 We then compute a path of 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(c)$
\end_inset

 which is consistent with our estimated SSB income elasticities, and we
 numerically integrate to find 
\begin_inset Formula $a(c)$
\end_inset

, which in turn identifies 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\theta)$
\end_inset

 at each ability gridpoint.
 Finally, we compute the implied ability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\theta)$
\end_inset

 which generates the observed income distribution.
 We then repeat this procedure with the new 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(c)$
\end_inset

 (which affects the FOC for SSB demand) and we iterate to convergence.
 In this manner, we find a non-parametric schedule of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(c)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\theta)$
\end_inset

 which is consistent with both the level of estimated soda consumption at
 each income, and with the estimated SSB income elasticities in our data.
 During simulations, we compute the nonparametric function 
\begin_inset Formula $a(c)$
\end_inset

 using linear interpolation (extrapolation) over 
\begin_inset Formula $\log(c)$
\end_inset

.
