 To isolate the role of the bias and elasticity of demand, the simulations
 in this figure assume constant values of each parameter across the income
 distribution (akin to row 10 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:SimulationResults"

\end_inset

), and zero externality cost.
 As a result, the optimal tax in the absence of distributional concerns
 (i.e., the optimal Pigouvian tax) lies on the 45-degree line, and departures
 from that line illustrate the effect of redistributive concerns on the
 optimal sin tax.
 The baseline (average) value of bias is represented in the figure by the
 vertical dashed line, and the baseline (average) demand elasticity is plotted
